HPLC method was used for comparison. To be specific, different concentration of CLZ solution was prepared with ethanol as solvent, and the standard curves were drawn by using HPLC method (HPLC condition was shown in 
                              Supporting Information
                           ). Then, the actual samples were determined by HPLC analysis (The actual sample was configured as above). The content of CLZ in the tablet was calculated according to the standard curve and the recovery rate was calculated. Finally, the results of two methods were compared.

As mentioned in introduction, most of the existing methods for the synthesis of CDs use small chemical molecules as precursors and toxic organic solvents as reaction solvents. their synthesis also usually requires a long reaction time at high temperature, which are not only detrimental to environmental protection and human health, but also consume a lot of energy. The unique properties of charcoal TCMs make them potential raw materials for preparing CDs. Herein, carbonized human hair was used as the raw material for the preparation of CDs. Because carbonized human hair was sintered from hair, the traditional method was applied to calcination the hair, and thus the carbonized human hair with fluorescence properties was obtained. Ulteriorly, carbonized human hair derived CDs (B-CDs) with a QY of 38% was obtained by one-step dialysis purification method. In comparison with the reported literatures (
                           Table S1
                        ), it can be easily seen that both the preparation method and the QY of B-CDs had great advantages.
